Which features are discrete?¶

These discrete values can classify the sample into a series of similar samples. In discrete features, are their values based on nouns? Or is it based on order? Or is it ratio-based? Or is it based on the interval class? In addition, this can help us choose the right graph for the data to visualize.

In this question, the discrete variables are: Survived, Sex and Embarked. Based on the sequence: Pclass.

Which features are numerical?¶

The value of these data varies from sample to sample. In numerical features, are their values discrete or continuous? Or is it based on time series? In addition, this can help us choose the right graph for the data to visualize.

In this problem, the continuous numerical features are: Age, Fare. Discrete values are: SibSp, Parch.

5. Hypothesis based on the above data analysis¶

Based on the above data analysis steps, we can temporarily draw the following assumptions.

Interrelationship:

We want to know how relevant each feature is to Survival. We hope to do this step this morning and match these correlation features to the modeled correlation features.

Complete data:

  1. We may go to complete the data under the Age feature, because it must be related to the survival rate.
  2. We may go to complete the data under the Embarked feature, because it may have a correlation with survival rate or other important features.

Correction data:

  1. The Ticket feature may need to be discarded from our analysis because its numerical repetition rate is as high as 22%, and there is probably no connection between Ticket and survival.
  2. The Cabin feature may also need to be discarded, because its value is very incomplete and contains more null values in both the training set and the test set.
  3. The PassengerId feature may also need to be discarded because it has no effect on survival The Name feature is relatively non-specific, and there is probably no direct connection with survival, so it may and should be discarded.

Create data:

  1. We can create a new Family feature based on the features of Parch and SibSp to get how many family members of each passenger have boarded the ship.
  2. We can further process the Name feature and extract the Title in the name as a new feature.
  3. We can create a new feature for the Age feature and convert its original continuous numerical feature into an ordered discrete feature.
  4. We can also create a Fare range feature if it is helpful to our analysis.

Classify:

Based on the previous problem description or existing data, we can also make the following hypotheses:

  1. Women (Sex=female) are more likely to survive.
  2. Children (Age<?) are also more likely to survive.
  3. Passengers in the upper class (Pclass=1) have a greater survival rate.

6. Analysis by converting some features¶

In order to verify the previous observations and hypotheses, we can simply analyze the correlation between the features through the pivoting feature method.

This method is only effective for those attributes that do not have particularly long and empty values, and only meaningful for those features that are classified (Sex), ordered (Pclass), and discrete (SibSp, Parch).

  1. Pclass: We observe that Pclass=1 has a large correlation with Survived (>0.5), so we can consider putting this feature into the later model.
  2. Sex: We can confirm that Sex=female has a survival rate of 74%.
  3. SibSp and Parch: Some values of these features are correlated with survived, but some are not correlated. So we may need to create a new feature based on these individual features or a series of features for further analysis.

The above conclusion can be obtained by the following operations:

7. Analysis by visualizing data¶

Now we can further analyze the data by visualizing the data and continue to verify whether our previous assumptions are correct.

The relationship between numerical features and Survived:

The histogram is very useful when used to analyze continuous numerical features, such as the feature Age. Its histogram value range (different age ranges) can help us identify some useful patterns.

By using the default or custom range of values (age range), the histogram can help us plot the distribution that the sample follows.

It can help us discover whether certain age ranges (such as babies) have a higher survival rate.

We can draw the histogram of Age through the following code:

In [18]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(train_data, col='Survived')
g.map(plt.hist, 'Age', bins=20)
plt.show()

Observed:

  1. Infants (Age<=4) have a higher survival rate (20 bins, each bin is 4 years old).
  2. All the elderly (Age=80) survived.
  3. A large number of passengers aged 15-25 did not survive.
  4. Passengers are mainly in the 15-35 age range.

In conclusion:

The above simple analysis verifies our previous assumptions:

  1. We need to take Age into the training model.
  2. Complete null value for Age feature.
  3. We should divide different age groups.

The relationship between numerical and serial features:¶

8. Processing data¶

We have collected some hypotheses and conclusions based on the data set and the requirements of the topic. Up to now, we have not processed any features or data.

Next, we will process the data with the goal of "correcting data", "creating data" and "completing data" based on the assumptions and conclusions we made before.

Modify the data by discarding features:¶

This step is a good start. By discarding certain features, we can process fewer data points and make analysis easier.According to our previous assumptions and conclusions, We hope to discard the two features of Cabin and Ticket.

It should be noted here that in order to keep the data consistent, we need to discard both the training set and the test set at the same time.

Specific steps are as follows:

Create new features from existing features:¶

Before discarding the two features of Name and PassengerId, we hope to extract the features of Titles from the Name feature and test the relationship between Titles and survival.

In the code below, we have extracted the Title feature through regular expressions. The regular expression is (\w+.), which will match the first word ending with "." in the Name feature. At the same time, specifying the parameter of expand=False will return a DataFrame.

In [24]:
for dataset in combine:
        dataset['Title'] = dataset.Name.str.extract('([A-Za-z]+)\.', expand=False)

New discovery:

When we drew the diagrams of Title, Age and Survived, we made the following new discoveries:

  1. Most Title segments correspond accurately to the age field, for example, Title is the average age of Master is 5 years old.
  2. There is a certain degree of distinction between titles of different groups and survival rates.
  3. Certain titles (=2/3) such as Mme and Lady have higher passenger survival rates, but certain titles (=5) such as Don, Rev, and Jonkheer have low passenger survival rates.

In conclusion:

  1. We decided to keep this new Title feature and add it to the training model.

Completing continuous numerical features¶

Now we can start to complete the data for those features that contain null or missing values. We will first complete the data for the Age feature.

Now let's summarize three methods for completing continuous numerical feature data:

  1. A simple method is to generate a random number, the range of this random number is between the mean and standard deviation of this feature

  2. A more accurate approach is to use the features related to it to make a guess. In this case, we found a correlation between Age, Sex and Pclass.

So we will use the median of a series of Pclass and Sex features as the guessed Age value.

So we will have a series of guesses such as: when Pclass=1 and Sex=0, when Pclass=1 and Sex=1, etc...

  1. The third method is to combine the above two methods. We can guess the missing Age value based on a series of combinations of Pclass and Sex and use the random number mentioned in the first method

Method 1 and Method 3 will introduce random noise into the model, and the results may be different multiple times. So we are more inclined to use method 2:

In [33]:
grid = sns.FacetGrid(train_data, row='Pclass', col='Sex', size=2.2, aspect=1.6)
grid.map(plt.hist, 'Age', alpha=.5, bins=20)
grid.add_legend()
plt.show()

C:\Users\huhon\anaconda3\lib\site-packages\seaborn\axisgrid.py:243: UserWarning: The `size` parameter has been renamed to `height`; please update your code.
  warnings.warn(msg, UserWarning)

We first prepare an empty array to store the guessed age. Because it is a combination of Pclass and Gender, the size of the array is 2x3:

In [34]:
guess_ages = np.zeros((2, 3))

Then we can iterate on Sex (0 or 1) and Pclass (1, 2, 3), and calculate the guess (Age) value obtained under the combination of 6:

In [35]:
for dataset in combine:
    for i in range(0, 2):
        for j in range(0, 3):
            guess_data = dataset[(dataset['Sex'] == i) & (dataset['Pclass'] == j+1)]['Age'].dropna()

            age_guess = guess_data.median()

            # Convert random age float to nearest .5 age
            guess_ages[i, j] = int(age_guess / 0.5 + 0.5) * 0.5

    for i in range(0, 2):
            for j in range(0, 3):
                dataset.loc[ (dataset.Age.isnull()) & (dataset.Sex == i) & (dataset.Pclass == j+1),
                             'Age'] = guess_ages[i,j]

    dataset['Age'] = dataset['Age'].astype(int)

9. Model, predict, and solve problems¶

Now we are ready to train the model. After the model is trained, we can apply it to problem solving. For the prediction problem, we have at least more than 60 algorithms to choose from.

So we must understand the type of problem and the needs of the solution, so as to narrow the scope of model selection. Now this problem is a classification and regression problem,

We want to find out the relationship between the output (Survived) and other features (Gender, Age, Port, etc.). Because the training set is given, this is a supervised learning in machine learning.

So the current demand for algorithms is: supervised learning plus classification and regression. According to this condition, we have the following models to choose from:

  1. Logistic Regression
  2. KNN
  3. SVM
  4. Naive Bayes classifier
  5. Decision Tree
  6. Random Forrest
  7. Perceptron
  8. Artificial neural network
  9. RVM or Relevance Vector Machine

Now we distinguish the training set from the test set:

In [50]:
X_train = train_data.drop('Survived', axis=1)

We can use Logistic Regression to verify the assumptions and conclusions we have made. This can be achieved by calculating the coefficient of the characteristic value. Positive coefficients can increase the log odds (thus increasing the probability), and negative coefficients will reduce the log odds (thus reducing the probability):

In [52]:
coeff_data = pd.DataFrame(train_data.columns.delete(0))
coeff_data.columns = ['Feature']
coeff_data["Correlation"] = pd.Series(logreg.coef_[0])
coeff_data.sort_values(by='Correlation', ascending=False)
Out[52]:
Feature Correlation
1 Sex 2.201619
5 Title 0.397888
2 Age 0.287011
4 Embarked 0.261473
6 IsAlone 0.126553
3 Fare -0.086655
7 Age*Class -0.311069
0 Pclass -0.750700

From the above results, we can see:

  1. Sex is the characteristic with the highest positive coefficient. This surface is that when the value of Sex increases (from male:0 to female:1), the probability of Survived=1 increases the most.
  2. Conversely, when Pclass increases, the probability of Survived=1 decreases the most.
  3. From the results, the new feature Age*Class we created is very useful because it has the second highest negative correlation with Survived.
  4. Title is the second highest positive coefficient feature.

Among them, decision tree and random forest have the highest correct rate, but we will choose the random forest algorithm here. Because Random forests are an ensemble learning method for classification (and regression) that operate by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the classes output by individual trees. The last but not the least, it makes up for the problem of decision tree overfitting.

As seen from previous data analysis and feature engineering results, Titanic passengers' survival law is in full compliance with the "gentleman concept" that has been recognized by the society-ladies and children first. The survival rate of women and children is much higher than that of others. But what we can make predictions, and since it is a prediction, there must be unpredictable circumstances. Therefore, I think the most important thing is not the predicted result (of course, the higher the accuracy rate, the better), but the laws and phenomena discovered after data analysis and processing in the entire project, and practical application of these experiences in subsequent projects to avoid a similar mistake. In China, there is a saying "The failure of the past is the lesson of the future." Simultaneously, the most difficult and most important thing in the entire project is not selecting models, but the acquisition of data, optimization work and feature engineering—the better the data, the better the model. By the way, I think I won't embark on the Titanic because as a 25-year-old man, I will devote my alive chance to other ladies or children.
